{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}} {{Infobox power station | name = Amrumbank West | image = | image_caption = | location_map = North Sea | location_map_caption = Location of Amrumbank West off the coast of Germany on the [[North Sea]] | coordinates = {{coord|54|30|N|7|48|E|region:DE_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | name_official = | country = Germany | location = North Sea, ~{{convert|35|km|abbr=on}} north of [[Helgoland]] | owner = E.ON | cost = | status = O | construction_began = | commissioned = 2015 | decommissioned = | ps_units_manu_model = | wind_hub_height = | wind_rotor_diameter = | wind_rated_speed = | wind_farm_type = | wind_site_elevation = | wind_site_usage = | wind_offshore_depth = | wind_offshore_distance = | ps_electrical_capacity = 302 MW | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | website = }} [[File:Map of the offshore wind power farms in the German Bight.png|thumb|240px|Amrumbank West's location in the wind farms of the German Bight]] '''Amrumbank West''' in a German [[offshore wind farm]] in the [[North Sea]] owned by [[E.ON]]. It is located about 35&nbsp;km northwest of the island of [[Heligoland]] and around 18&nbsp;km south-west of the [[Amrum Bank]] sandbank. It consists of 80 turbines in waters 19–24 m deep.<ref name=geo>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1088/1468-6996/16/3/034605|pmid=27877792|pmc=5099829| title = Geosynthetics in geoenvironmental engineering| journal = Science and Technology of Advanced Materials| volume = 16| issue = 3| pages = 034605| year = 2015| last1 = Müller | first1 = W. W. | last2 = Saathoff | first2 = F. |bibcode=2015STAdM..16c4605M}}</ref>
==Construction== Construction cost was around {{euro|1 billion}}.<ref>[http://www.eon.com/content/dam/eon-com/en/downloads/1/111216_Factsheet_Amrumbank_dt.pdf ''Factsheet Amrumbank West''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924001400/http://www.eon.com/content/dam/eon-com/en/downloads/1/111216_Factsheet_Amrumbank_dt.pdf |date=24 September 2015 }} (PDF; 1,2&nbsp;MB). Eon, retrieved 21 April 2012.</ref> The project was delayed 15 months by the lack of power lines.<ref>[http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/energy/german-wind-energy-plans-in-the-doldrums German wind energy plans in the doldrums]. Thenational.ae (6 March 2012). Retrieved on 2015-05-10.</ref> The 80 wind turbines are Siemens SWT-3.6–120 with a rated power of 3.6 MW and a rotor diameter of 120 meters.<ref>[http://www.siemens.com/press/de/pressemitteilungen/?press=/de/pressemitteilungen/2011/energy/wind-power/ewp201112021.htm ''Siemens sichert sich Auftrag für Offshore-Windkraftwerk in Deutschland.''] Siemens, 15 December 2011, retrieved 23 December 2011.</ref> Offshore construction began in 2013, and the first turbine was installed in February 2015. The wind farm was commissioned at the end of 2015.
==Seabed protection== [[File:Geoprotection of off-shore wind energy turbines.png|thumb|240px|Installation of turbine piles at Amrumbank West through the erosion protection layers.<ref name=geo/>]] The seabed surface at the construction site mainly consists of sand. It was initially reinforced by a 2.4-m-thick layer of large stones. However, this hindered installation of the turbine piles, which should be driven through the protection layer deep into the seabed. Therefore, stones were replaced by two layers of [[geotextile]] containers, i.e., sandbags made of a special damage-resistant nonwoven geotextile. Empty bags had a size of 1.45 × 2.38 m and could accommodate 1 m<sup>3</sup> of sand; they were filled on the [[Rømø]] island up to 80 vol% and weighed 1400 kg each. The seabed protection withstood the [[St. Jude storm]] in October 2013 and [[Cyclone Xaver]] in December 2013. Starting from December 2013, turbine piles 6 m in diameter were driven through the erosion protection layers.<ref name=geo/>
