{{other uses|Donkey punch (disambiguation)}} [[File:DonkeyPuncher-Oct1941.jpg|thumb|320px|A "donkey puncher" on the job in a [[Gyppo logger|gyppo logging]] operation in [[Tillamook County, Oregon]]. (October 1941)]] A '''donkey puncher''' is the operator of a small [[steam donkey]], a machine used in [[logging]] in the 19th and 20th centuries.<ref name="barman">{{cite book|last=Barman|first= Jean |year=2007|title=The West Beyond the West: A History of British Columbia|publisher=[[University of Toronto Press]]| ISBN= 9780802093097}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Running Springs|first=Stanley E.|last=Bellamy|page=28|year=2007|series=Images of America|publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]]|location=[[Charleston, South Carolina]]|isbn= 0738546798}}</ref>
==Description==
[[Image:Dcasteamdonkey.jpg|thumb|right|[[Steam donkey]] on display at [[Disney California Adventure Park]] theme park]]
A donkey consists of a [[steam boiler]] and [[steam engine]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Coos County|first=Lise|last=Hull|page=53|series=Images of America|year=2007|isbn= 0738548030|publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Learning about the old way to log|work=[[The Columbian]]|url=http://www.columbian.com/news/2011/jul/02/learning-about-the-old-way-to-log/|date=July 2, 2011|accessdate=September 13, 2012|first=Bob|last=Albrecht}}</ref> connected to a winch mounted on a sled called a [[donkey sled]].<ref>{{cite book|page=92|title=Forever Green: The History and Hope of the American Forest |year=2001|first=Chuck |last=Leavell|author2=Mary Welch |publisher=[[Mercer University Press]]|isbn= 0865549001 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|page=127; Volume 39|last=Bolling|first=Arthur Johnson (editor)|title=Chicago Lumberman|publisher=Lumber World Review; Lumber Review Company|date=July–December 1920|location=[[Chicago, Illinois]]}}</ref> The donkeys were moved by simply dragging themselves with the [[winch]] line. They were used to move logs, by attaching lines to the logs and hauling them.<ref name="MacConomy">{{cite book|last=MacConomy|first=Alma Deane|year=1968|title=Odd Jobs in Lumbering|publisher=Putnam Publishing Group|ISBN =978-0399604973}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|page=103|title=Hard Traveling: A Portrait of Work Life in the New Northwest|first=Carlos Arnaldo |last=Schwantes|year=1999|isbn= 0803292708|publisher=[[University of Nebraska Press]]}}</ref>
The donkey puncher was the machine operator and [[engineer]].<ref>{{cite book|page=369|title=Oregon: End of the Trail - American Guide Series|author=Federal Writers Project|isbn= 0403021863|year=1972|publisher=Scholarly Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Annapolis and the Gualala River|first=Tammy|last=Durston|page=19|series=Images of America|publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]]|isbn= 0738581143|year=2010}}</ref> Use of the term gained currency in 1920.<ref>{{cite book|page=211|title=The Concise New Partridge Dictionary of Slang|year=2007|first=Tom|last=Dalzell|author2=Terry Victor|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn= 0415212596 }}</ref> In later times the donkey puncher was too far away from the end of the line for verbal communication, so [[whistle code]]s ([[steam whistle]]s) were employed.<ref name=rombes /> The whistle operator was known as a [[whistle punk]],<ref name=rombes /><ref>{{cite book|title=On the Harbor: From Black Friday to Nirvana|first=John C.|last=Hughes|author2=Ryan Teague Beckwith|year=2010|page=16|isbn= 1932173501|publisher=Stephens Press LLC}}</ref> who was placed between the men attaching the cables ([[choker setter]]s),<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Beaver County Times]]|date=June 24, 1969|title=Balloons assume role of Paul Bunyan's Blue Ox|author=[[United Press International]]|page=C15|location=[[Pennsylvania]]}}</ref> and the donkey puncher, so that he could see the choker setters.<ref name=rombes /><ref>{{cite news|title=Lingo of a mighty industry; Whistle Punk|work=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|date=April 6, 1940|page=4|first=Bob|last=Francis}}</ref> When the cables were attached, a series of whistle blows signaled the donkey to begin pulling and the choker setters to stay out of harm's way.<ref name=rombes>{{cite book|last=Rombes|pages=305–310|title=A Cultural Dictionary of Punk, 1974-1982| first=Nicholas|publisher= Continuum|year=2009|isbn= 0826427790}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[The Owosso Argus Press]]|title=Woodsmen on coast have own language|date=August 8, 1921|location=[[Owosso, Michigan]]|page=8}}</ref> This is an oversimplification of a closely orchestrated sequence of operations, where mistakes were often fatal and where good men stood in line for the jobs.<ref>{{cite book|first=Donald|last=MacKay|title=The Lumberjacks|pages=179–181|year=2007|publisher=Natural Heritage Books|isbn=9781550027730}}</ref> Although the steam engine, and its whistle, have been replaced by [[gasoline]] and [[diesel engine]]s,<ref>{{cite book|title=Chainsaws in the Cathedral|year=1999|page=150|first=Peter|last=Trower|publisher=Ekstasis Editions Canada Ltd.|isbn=978-1896860466}}</ref> the whistle codes are still used in many current [[logging]] operations. The whistle has been replaced largely with [[airhorn]]s.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Ellensburg Daily Record]]|title=Loggers roll into Seattle for rally|date=June 3, 1989|page=3|location=[[Seattle, Washington]]|author=[[United Press International]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Logging convoy is crossing Wyoming|work=[[Merced Sun-Star]]|date=May 18, 1977|location=[[Cheyenne, Wyoming]]|author=[[Associated Press]]|page=15}}</ref>
