{{Infobox power station | name = Embilipitiya Power Station | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Sri Lanka | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | location_map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|06|17|06|N|80|50|56|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | country = Sri Lanka | location = [[Embilipitiya]] | status = Operational | construction_began = | commissioned = 2005 | decommissioned = | cost = [[Sri Lankan Rupee|Rs.]] 8 billion | owner = [[Aitken Spence]] | operator = {{Nowrap|Ace Power Embilipitiya (Pvt) Ltd}} | th_fuel_primary = [[Fuel oil]] | th_fuel_secondary = | th_fuel_tertiary = | th_technology = | th_feed_mine = | th_cogeneration = | th_combined_cycle = | th_cooling_source = | ps_units_operational = | ps_units_manu_model = [[Caterpillar Inc.]] 16CM32C | ps_units_uc = | ps_units_planned = | ps_units_cancelled = | ps_units_decommissioned= 14 × 7.11 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_thermal_capacity = | ps_electrical_capacity = 100 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | ps_storage_hours = | ps_annual_generation = | website = | extra = }}
The '''Embilipitiya Power Station''' (also sometimes referred to as '''Ace Power Embilipitiya''') is a {{Nowrap|100 [[Megawatt|MW]]}} thermal [[power station]] in [[Embilipitiya]], [[Sri Lanka]]. The [[fuel oil|heavy fuel oil]]-run power station was commissioned in March 2005, and was operated by [[Aitken Spence]] (sometimes shortened to ''Ace''). The power station consisted of fourteen {{Nowrap|[[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar]] 16CM32C}} generation units of {{Nowrap|7.11 MW}} each, which consumed approximately {{Nowrap|550 [[tonne]]s}} of fuel oil per day. The [[Ministry of Power and Energy]] discontinued purchasing power from the private power station after its license expired in 2015, and hence was subsequently decommissioned.<ref name=DailyNews2011>{{cite news|last1=Jayakody|first1=Jayasri|title=Mulls plants in Bangladesh, Indonesia: Ace Power to venture overseas|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2011/08/15/bus01.asp|accessdate=7 November 2015|publisher=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)|Daily News]]|date=15 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=We decided to close down 03 thermal power generation plants that supplied electricity to the Ceylon Electricity Board|url=http://powermin.gov.lk/english/?page_id=3711|publisher=[[Ministry of Power and Energy]]|accessdate=7 November 2015|date=15 May 2015}}</ref> In March 2016 [[Ceylon Electricity Board]] decided to recommission the plant due to high electricity demand in the country.<ref name=DailyMirror2016>{{cite news|last1=Pradeep|first1=Chaturanga|title=CEB to buy power from ACE|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/107674/CEB-to-buy-power-from-ACE|accessdate=26 February 2018|publisher=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)|Daily Mirror]]|date=31 March 2016}}</ref> The facility cost approximately [[Sri Lankan Rupee|Rs.]] 8 billion to develop, and is built on a {{Convert|44|acre|ha|abbr=on|adj=on}} land on a 33-year lease.<ref name=DailyNews2011 /><ref>{{cite web|title=Diesel and Gas-Engine Power Plants in Sri Lanka|url=http://www.industcards.com/ic-sri-lanka.htm|publisher=Industcards.com|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref> {{Clear}}
