{{redirect|Salt lick}}
[[File:Bos gaurus.jpg|thumb|[[Gaur]] at a natural salt lick]] A '''mineral lick''' (also known as a '''salt lick''') is a place where [[animal]]s can go to [[licking|lick]] essential [[mineral nutrients]] from a deposit of [[salt (chemistry)|salts]] and other [[mineral]]s. Mineral licks can be naturally occurring or artificial (such as blocks of [[salt]] that farmers place in [[pasture]]s for [[livestock]] to lick). Natural licks are common, and they provide essential elements such as [[phosphorus]] and the [[biometal (biology)|biometals]] ([[sodium]], [[calcium]], [[iron]], [[zinc]], and [[trace element]]s) required in the springtime for [[bone]], [[muscle]] and other growth in [[deer]] and other wildlife, such as [[moose]], [[elephant]]s, [[tapir]]s, [[cattle]], [[woodchuck]]s, [[domestic sheep]], [[fox squirrel]]s, [[mountain goat]]s and [[porcupine]]s. Such licks are especially important in [[ecosystem]]s with poor general availability of nutrients. Harsh weather exposes salty [[mineral]] deposits that draw animals from miles away for a taste of needed nutrients. It is thought that certain fauna can detect [[calcium]] in salt licks.<ref>C. Michael Hogan. 2010. [http://www.eoearth.org/article/Calcium?topic=49557 ''Calcium''. eds. A.Jorgensen, C.Cleveland. Encyclopedia of Earth]. National Council for Science and the Environment.</ref>
==Overview== Many animals regularly visit mineral licks to consume [[clay]], supplementing their [[Dietary mineral|diet]] with nutrients and minerals. Some animals require the minerals at these sites not for nutrition, but to ward off the effects of secondary compounds that are included in the arsenal of plant defences against herbivory.<ref name="Voigt08">{{cite journal | last1=Voigt | first1=C. C. | last2=Capps | first2=K. A. | last3=Dechmann | first3=D. K. N. | last4=Michner | first4=R. H. | last5=Kunz | first5=T. H. | year=2008 | title=Nutrition or detoxification: Why bats visit mineral licks of the Amazonian rainforest | journal=PLoS ONE | volume=3 | issue=4 | pages=e2011 | doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0002011 | url=http://www.plosone.org/article/fetchObjectAttachment.action;jsessionid=C3C2F69980DAC80E2C391108FBC39387.ambra01?uri=info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0002011&representation=PDF}}</ref> The mineral contents of these sites usually contain [[calcium]] (Ca), [[magnesium]] (Mg), [[sulfur]] (S) [[phosphorus]] (P), [[potassium]] (K), and [[sodium]] (Na).<ref name="Emmons79">{{cite journal | last1=Emmons | first1=L. H. | last2=Stark | first2=N. M. | title=Elemental composition of a natural mineral lick in Amazonia | journal=Biotropica | volume=11 | issue=4 | pages=311–313 | year=1979 | jstor=2387925 | doi=10.2307/2387925}}</ref><ref name="Blake11">{{cite journal | last1=Black | first1=J. G. | last2=Mosquera | first2=D. | last3=Guerra | first3=J. | last4=Loiselle | first4=B. A. | last5=Romo | first5=D. | last6=Swing | first6=K. | year=2011 | title=Mineral licks as diversity hotspots in lowland forest of eastern Ecuador | journal=Diversity | volume=3 | issue=2 | pages=217–234 | doi=10.3390/d3020217 | url=http://www.mdpi.com/1424-2818/3/2/217/pdf}}</ref><ref name="Ayotte08">{{cite journal|last1=Ayotte |first1=J. B. |last2=Parker |first2=K. L. |last3=Gillingham |first3=M. P. |title=Use of natural licks by four species of ungulates in northern British Columbia |journal=Journal of Mammalogy |volume=89 |issue=4 |pages=1041–1050 |year=2008 |url=http://www.asmjournals.org/doi/pdf/10.1644/07-MAMM-A-345.1 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130414092646/http://www.asmjournals.org/doi/pdf/10.1644/07-MAMM-A-345.1 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2013-04-14 |doi=10.1644/07-MAMM-A-345.1 }}</ref><ref name="Atwood03">{{cite journal | last1=Atwood | first1=T. C. | last2=Weeks | first2=H. P. | title=Sex-specific patterns of mineral lick preference in white-tailed deer | journal=Northeastern Naturalist | volume=10 | issue=4 | pages=409–414 | year=2003 | jstor=3858657 | doi=10.2307/3858657}}</ref> Mineral lick sites play a critical role in the ecology and diversity of organisms that visit these sites, but little is still understood about the dietary benefits.
The paths animals made to natural mineral licks and watering holes became the hunting paths predators and early man used for hunting. It is theorized that these salt and water paths became trails and later roads for early man.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,925341,00.html|title=A Brief History of Salt|date=1982-03-15|work=Time|access-date=2018-04-16|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref>
Nonetheless, many studies have identified other uses and nutritional benefits from other micronutrients that exist at these sites, including [[selenium]] (Se), [[cobalt]] (Co) and/or [[molybdenum]] (Mo).<ref name="Mills06">{{cite journal | last1=Mills | first1=A. | last2=Milewski | first2=A. | title=Geophagy and nutrient supplementation in the Ngorongoro Conservation Area, Tanzania, with particular reference to selenium, cobalt and molybdenum | journal=Journal of Zoology | volume=271 | issue=1 | pages=110–118 | year=2007 | doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.2006.00241.x}}</ref><ref name="Ayotte06">{{cite journal|last1=Ayotte |first1=J. B. |last2=Parker |first2=K. L. |last3=Arocena |first3=J. M. |last4=Gillingham |first4=M. P. |title=Chemical composition of lick soils: Functions of soil ingestion by four ungulate species |journal=Journal of Mammalogy |volume=87 |issue=5 |pages=878–888 |year=2006 |url=http://www.asmjournals.org/doi/pdf/10.1644/06-MAMM-A-055R1.1 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130414061518/http://www.asmjournals.org/doi/pdf/10.1644/06-MAMM-A-055R1.1 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2013-04-14 |doi=10.1644/06-MAMM-A-055R1.1 }}</ref> In addition to the utilization of mineral licks, many animals suffer from [[roadkill|traffic collisions]] as they gather to lick salts accumulated on road surfaces. Animals also consume soil ([[geophagy]]) to obtain minerals, such as moose from Canada mining for minerals from the root wads of fallen trees.<ref name="Rea07">{{cite journal|last1=Rea |first1=R. |title=Mining and geophagy of root wad soils by moose in winter |journal=Wildlife Afield |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=86–87 |url=http://www.wildlifebc.org/UserFiles/File/4_1_Rea.pdf |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325194218/http://www.wildlifebc.org/UserFiles/File/4_1_Rea.pdf |archivedate=2012-03-25 |df= }}</ref><ref name="Klassen08">{{cite journal | last1=Klassen | first1=N. A. | last2=Rea | first2=R. V. | title=What do we know about nocturnal activity of moose? | journal=Alces | volume=44 | pages=101–109 | year=2008 | url=http://alcesjournal.org/index.php/alces/article/view/40/39}}</ref>
==Artificial salt licks== People use salt licks in the [[animal husbandry|husbandry]] of [[livestock]] and to attract or maintain [[wildlife]], whether it be for viewing, photography, farming, or hunting purposes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hrcranch.com/managing-the-deer-herd-on-ranch/|title=Managing the Deer Herd on Your Ranch {{!}} Hortenstine Ranch Company|date=2017-10-03|work=Hortenstine Ranch Company|access-date=2018-10-03|language=en-US}}</ref> Maintaining artificial salt licks as a form of [[Bait (luring substance)|baiting]] is illegal in some states in the United States, but legal in others.<ref name="Atwood03" />{{rp|413}}
<gallery class="center" caption="" widths="220px" heights="160px"> Image:salt lick 01.jpg|Block of salt mounted on a post in [[Sopot]], [[Poland]] File:Pilanesberg-Salt lick-001.jpg|[[Giraffe]] and [[wildebeest]] at an artificial salt lick in the [[Pilanesberg Game Reserve]], South Africa </gallery>
==In American history== The [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous people of America]] and the [[Longhunter|Long Hunters]] watched salt licks to hunt game. Many became well known including [[Bledsoe's Station|Bledsoe Lick]] in [[Sumner County, Tennessee]]; the [[Blue Licks Battlefield State Park|Blue Lick]] in central [[Kentucky]]; 'Great Buffalo Lick' in [[Kanawha Salines]], now present-day [[Malden, West Virginia]]; the [[French Lick, Indiana|French Lick]] in southern [[Indiana]]; and the [[Blackwater Lick]] in [[Blackwater, Lee County, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mylonghunters.info/blackwater-virginia|title=My Long Hunters - Blackwater, VirginiaBlackwater, Virginia - My Long Hunters|website=mylonghunters.info}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=December 2011}}
==Mythology== In [[Norse mythology]], before the creation of the world, it was the divine cow [[Auðumbla|Audhumla]] who, through her licking of the cosmic salt ice, gave form to [[Búri|Buri]], ancestor of the [[Æsir|gods]] and grandfather of [[Odin]]. On the first day as Audhumla licked, Buri's hair appeared from the ice, on the second day his head and on the third his body.<ref>[[Prose Edda]] by [[Snorri Sturluson]]</ref>
